Part I - PROSPER LOAN DATA EXPLORATION¶

by OPARA FEBECHUKWU CHINONYEREM¶

Introduction¶

The dataset is a Prosper Loan data, which contains 82 fields. We would be focusing on these fields in our exploration, which are:

  1. TotalProsperLoans: Number of Prosper loans the borrower had at the time they created this listing. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  2. OnTimeProsperPayments: Number of on time payments the borrower had made on Prosper loans at the time they created this listing. This value will be null if the borrower has no prior loans.
  3. ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate: Number of payments the borrower made on Prosper loans that were less than one month late at the time they created this listing. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  4. ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate: Number of payments the borrower made on Prosper loans that were greater than one month late at the time they created this listing. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  5. ProsperPrincipalBorrowed: Total principal borrowed on Prosper loans at the time the listing was created. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  6. ProsperPrincipalOutstanding:Principal outstanding on Prosper loans at the time the listing was created. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  7. LoanCurrentDaysDelinquent: The number of days delinquent.
  8. LoanFirstDefaultedCycleNumber: The cycle the loan was charged off. If the loan has not charged off the value will be null.
  9. LoanMonthsSinceOrigination: Number of months since the loan originated.
  10. LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  11. LoanOriginationDate:The date the loan was originated.
  12. MonthlyLoanPayment:The scheduled monthly loan payment.
  13. LP_CustomerPayments: Pre charge-off cumulative gross payments made by the borrower on the loan. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.
  14. LP_CustomerPrincipalPayments: Pre charge-off cumulative principal payments made by the borrower on the loan. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.
  15. LP_InterestandFees: Pre charge-off cumulative interest and fees paid by the borrower. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.
  16. LP_GrossPrincipalLoss: The gross charged off amount of the loan.
  17. LP_NetPrincipalLoss: The principal that remains uncollected after any recoveries.
  18. Investors: The number of investors that funded the loan.
  19. LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  20. Recommendations: Number of recommendations the borrower had at the time the listing was created.
  21. InvestmentFromFriendsCount: Number of friends that made an investment in the loan.
  22. InvestmentFromFriendsAmount: Dollar amount of investments that were made by friends.
  23. StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  24. Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  25. MemberKey: The unique key that is associated with the borrower. This is the same identifier that is used in the API member object.
  26. DebtToIncomeRatio:The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).
  27. LenderYield: The Lender yield on the loan. Lender yield is equal to the interest rate on the loan less the servicing fee.
  28. BorrowerRate:The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  29. EstimatedEffectiveYield: Effective yield is equal to the borrower interest rate (i) minus the servicing fee rate, (ii) minus estimated uncollected interest on charge-offs, (iii) plus estimated collected late fees. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  30. EstimatedLoss: Estimated loss is the estimated principal loss on charge-offs. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  31. EstimatedReturn: The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created. Estimated return is the difference between the Estimated Effective Yield and the Estimated Loss Rate. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  32. ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

'''Function to make a field a categorical type - nominal or ordinal
    Parameter:
    listOfCategory: This is a list bearing the categories of the field which follows the 
    exact order specified for ordinal fields and for nominal fields the order in which
    the values appear in the list is not sticked to.
    
    field: The dataframe column to make of type category
    
    order: A boolean value that specifies if the category type is of 
    type ordinal or nominal i.e if the order in which the listOfCategory was entered
    should be sticked to or not
'''
def makeCategorical(listOfCategory, field,order):
    #splits the version of the pandas library we are using at the . part
    pd_ver = pd.__version__.split(".")
    #checks if the element at index 0 is > 0 and the element at index 1 >= 21
    if (int(pd_ver[0]) > 0) or (int(pd_ver[1]) >= 21): # i.e we are dealing with pandas version of v0.21 or later
        #Creates the categorical type 
        category = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = order, categories = listOfCategory)
        #assigns the categorical type to the field/column
        df_loan[field] = df_loan[field].astype(category)
    else: # for pandas version of v.20
        #make the field of type category without having to create a categorical type first
        df_loan[field] = df_loan[field] .astype('category', ordered = order, categories = listOfCategory)

'''Creates a barChart
    dat: The dataframe to pull the data from
    column: The column to create the barchart for
    colo: The color for the bars
'''
def barChart(dat, column, colo):
    #Creates the barchart with order being the order the index values of series returned by value_counts
    sb.countplot(data=dat, x=column,color=colo,order=dat[column].value_counts().index);
    #rotates the tick values of x axis to be at 90 degree
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

''' Plots a histogram
    dat: The dataframe to pull the data from
    xcolumn: The column of the dataframe to plot the frequency distribution
    bins: The bin sizing to be used in plotting the histogram
    xlab: The label of the x axis
    ylab: The label of the y axis
    title: The title of the plot
'''
def histogram(dat, xcolumn, colo, bins, xlab,ylab,title):
    #plots the histogram using the bin sizes issued
    plt.hist(data=dat, x=xcolumn, bins=bins);
    plt.xlabel(xlab)
    plt.ylabel(ylab)
    plt.title(title)

In [54]:
'''Sets the ProsperScore of value 11 to the modal Value
    x: The ProsperScore to be tested if it's 11
    returns the value if it isn't 11 or returns the mode which is 4 if it is 11
'''
def setToMode(x):
    if x == 11:
        return 4
    else:
        return x
    
df_loan['ProsperScore'] = df_loan['ProsperScore'].apply(lambda x: setToMode(x))

Unusual Point and Transformation Performed on the Dataset¶

One unusual point I discovered was a Prosper Score of 11, whereas the set is from 1-10, I simply made all ProsperScores equal to 11 to become the modal value 4. In order to view the distribution of certain data sets, I had to issue a customized bin to the histogram function I wrote and for some I had to do a log transform on the y axis.

Operation performed to Tidy Data set¶

The data had ordinal values of Prosper score showing as float type I had to clean it and make it of type Category, also the nominal type of Loan Status that was showing as object type was also made an unordered category type. A prosper score of 11 was turned to the modal value of 4, since we have prosper score of 1-10 and 11 is not among the set.

'''Function to create a Bivariate scatter plot
df: dataframe to pull the data from
col_x: the x axis column
col_y: the y axis column
alpha: the transparency to apply to the scatter plot
xlab: x axis description
ylab: y axis description
title: the title of the plot
'''
def scatterPlot(df, col_x, col_y, alpha, xlab, ylab, title):
    plt.scatter(data=df, x=col_x,y=col_y,alpha=alpha);
    plt.xlabel(xlab)
    plt.ylabel(ylab)
    plt.title(title)

In [14]:
''' Function to create a violin plot
df: dataframe to pull the data from
xcol: the column for the x axis
ycol: the column for the y axis
colo: the color for the violins
inne: whether to include the inner box plot
xlab: the x axis description
ylab: the y axis description
title: the title of the plot
'''
def violin(df, xcol, ycol, colo, inne, xlab, ylab, title):
    sb.violinplot(data=df, x=xcol, y=ycol, color=colo, inner=inne);
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.xlabel(xlab)
    plt.ylabel(ylab)
    plt.title(title)

In [65]:
'''A function to create a clustered bar chart
 df: the dataframe to pull the data from
 x_col: the column that should be on x axis
 hue_col: the column that the hue should be applied to
 xlab: x axis description
 ylab: y axis description
 titl: the title of chart
'''
def clusteredBarChart(df, x_col, hue_col, xlab,ylab,titl):
    sb.countplot(data=df,x=x_col,hue=hue_col);
    plt.xlabel(xlab)
    plt.ylabel(ylab)
    plt.title(titl)

How feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset¶

  1. LenderYield and LoanOriginalAmount resulted to a vertical linear relationship, i.e. the same amount of LoanOriginalAmount may give different LenderYield depending on what the BorrowerRate is, hence there is need for a multivariate plot of LenderYield, LoanOriginalAmount and BorrowerRate.
  2. LenderYield and MonthlyLoanPayment are partially related i.e. LenderYield increases or decreases partially with MonthlyLoanPayment
  3. The BorrowerRate and LoanOriginalAmount is related by x = constant, i.e. no matter the value of BorrowerRate, LoanOriginalAmount remains constant, i.e high amounts of loans are not issued at a higher Borrower rate, so Prosper needs to look into this, high value loans at short term should have lower borrower rate and high value loans at long term should have a higher borrower rate to increase yield incase of default along the process, but we are not seeing that pattern above.
  4. BorrowerRate and MonthlyLoanPayment have the same relationship existing between them as the one existing between LenderYield and MonthlyLoanPayment.
  5. The relationship between LoanOriginalAmount and Term is that Loans of term 12 have values 0.1 to 5000 more, as the violin is looking fat at this region.High amount of loans seem to have term 36 and 60 and low amount of loans seem to have term 12. Depending on what Prosper mission is in the finance industry, I think there needs to be a more balance in mix of loan amounts and term, i.e more short term loans of high figures at an appropriate interest rate should be issued.
  6. Loans of term 36 and 60 have MonthlyLoanPayments that are less as compared to loans of term 12.
  7. LoanOriginalAmount of 0-5000 values are much in less risky loans of ProsperScore of 1-4 and less risky loans of high values (ProsperScore of 7-10 and LoanOriginalAmount of 15000-35000) are not much.
  8. More risky loans (ProsperScore of 1-3) have small values of monthly loan payment (of 0-500) which isn't appreciable but before conclusion we need to see the relationship between the two variables and LoanOriginalAmount.
  9. Loans of term 60 and 36 have more on time payments of 0-20 than loans of term 12 but loans of term 12 have on time payments 20-40 more than the both. Recall that from above that univariate exploration that loans of term 36 have a higher frequency in Prosper loans. Loan terms does not explicitly affect on time payments.
  10. Less risky loans (ProsperScore of 10) have higher value of OnTimeProsperPayments but it isn't explicit.
  11. Majority of customers who have low outstanding principal were given loans of term 12 and 36 and majority of customers who have high outstanding principal were given loan of term 60. At this point, it seems Prosper is also a poverty alleviating venture.
  12. Customers with short term loans have the LP_GrossPrincipalLoss and LP_NetPrincipalLoss less than customers with long term loans but it isn't explicit.
  13. Relationship between LoanStatus and LoanOriginalAmount: More lesser loans are cancelled, chargedoff, completed, defaulted and in the final payment in progress LoanStatus than higher loans, no pattern is observed explicitly but in the relationship of the two, there is need to give more loans within [10000, 25000] than loans within [0,5000] and reduce the risk associated with them by making them short term loans with MonthlyLoanPayment of higher figures, this will be best visualized in a multivariate plot of LoanOriginalAmount, LoanStatus and MonthlyLoanPayment.
  14. Relationship between LoanOriginalAmount and LoanStatus: Cancelled, charged-off, completed, defaulted seemed much at [0-500] because we have smaller loans in our portfolio than higher loans.
  15. Relationship between LoanStatus and StatedMonthlyIncome: Most Prosper customers are low income earners, no wonder the [0-5000] high population of LoanOriginalAmount. To have higher profits, Prosper needs to take more risk by giving out higher loans to high income earners backed up properly by friends investment.

  16. In the relationship between BorrowerRate and DebtToIncomeRatio, the y axis variable seems to be constant at 0 or 10 no matter the value of Borrower rate indicating that Prosper is not considering the customers debt to income ratio in marking out borrower rates for loans, saliently implying that their mission may not be poverty alleviation but profit making, as majority of points reside at debt to income ratio of 0. ### How other features (not the main feature(s) of interest) relate with each other

  17. The relationship between MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount is that Prosper loans of 35000 were having MonthlyLoanPayment almost same with some loans of 20000 and 25000, which isn't ok. Larger loan amounts should have larger monthly loan repayment amount to reduce the risk of such loans, hence there exist a need to view the multivariate relationship between MonthlyLoanPayment, LoanOriginalAmount and ProsperScore.

  18. ProsperPrincipalBorrowed and ProsperPrincipalOutstanding seem to have a relationship where ProsperPrincipalOutstanding remains constant for whatever principal value borrowed and then it also seems to have a linear relationship.
  19. Relationship between ProsperPrincipalOutstanding and TotalProsperLoans: Prosper portfolio seems to be healthy as customers who have high principal outstanding [15000,20000) have 1,2,3,4,5 total prosper loans running and customers with 0-10000 principal outstanding have 6,7,8 loans running. '''Function to create a faceted scatter plot
    df: the dataframe to pull the data from
    hueColumn: The categorical column
    siz: The size of the facet
    colX: Numeric column on the x axis
    colY: Numeric column on the y axis
    xscale: The scale transform to apply to x axis
    yscale: The scale transform to apply to y axis
    xticks: The ticks to be used on the x axis
    yticks: The ticks to be used on the y axis
    palete: The color palete to use for the hueColumn
    alpha: The transparency value of the scatter plot
'''
def facetedScatterPlot(df, hueColumn, siz, colX, colY, xscale, yscale, xticks, yticks,palete, alpha):
    g=sb.FacetGrid(data=df,hue=hueColumn,height=siz,aspect=1.5,palette=palete)
    g.map(plt.scatter, colX, colY, alpha = alpha)
    #set the x axis transform to log if log is given
    if xscale=='log':
        g.set(xscale='log')
    #set the y axis transform to log if log is given
    if yscale=='log':
        g.set(xscale='log')
    #if xticks is not an empty list, set the xtick
    if xticks != []:
        g.set(xticks=xticks, xticklabels=xticks)
    #if yticks is not an empty list, set the ytick
    if yticks != []:
        g.set(yticks=yticks, yticklabels=yticks)
    g.add_legend()

'''function to create a heatmap
df: dataframe to pull the data from
min_x : minimum value of column on x axis
max_x: maximum value of column on the x axis
step_x: the increment value in creating the x axis bin sizes
colX: The column on the x axis
min_y: minimum value of column on y axis
max_y: maximum value of column on the y axis
step_y: the increment value in creating the y axis bin sizes
colY: The column on the y axis
colZ: the column that is used as the weights'''
def heatMap(df, min_x, max_x, step_x, colX, min_y, max_y,step_y, colY, colZ):
    bins_x = np.arange(min_x, max_x+step_x,step_x)
    bins_y = np.arange(min_y, max_y+step_y,step_y)
    #draw 2d histogram - heat map
    plt.hist2d(data=df, x=colX, y=colY, cmin=0.5,cmap='viridis_r',  bins=[bins_x,bins_y], weights=df[colZ]);
